pipeline_messages.content:
You are an expert writing quality judge. You will evaluate three drafts
against a set of personalized rubric criteria. You also have access to the user's
recent conversation history for additional context about their preferences.

The three drafts are:
- Draft A = the **rubric-guided** draft (written following the user's rubric criteria)
- Draft B = the **generic** draft (written with no rubric — just competent writing)
- Draft C = the **original preference** draft (written from the user's stated preferences, before the rubric was created)

DRAFT A (rubric-guided):
Marcus chose the early shift.

He picked it because it ended at 2 p.m., which meant he could walk from the warehouse to the library by 2:45, sit down with his workbook before his daughter's school bus arrived at 4:15, and still be home to make dinner. That was his schedule, three evenings a week, for seven months. He built it himself, around a family that needed him present and a reading level he had decided, at 34, was no longer going to hold him back.

By spring, Marcus had completed our adult literacy program and was helping his daughter with her third-grade homework for the first time.

He is one of 214 adults who enrolled in the program this year. Sixty-one percent finished. That completion rate is the highest we have recorded — and it did not happen by accident. It happened because people like Marcus designed their own paths through the program and held to them.

Your decision to give before December 31 is what keeps this program running through the spring enrollment cycle. A gift of $150 sustains one participant — their materials, their instruction hours, their seat — for a full twelve weeks. If 75 donors make that choice this month, 75 more adults start the new year the way Marcus did: with a plan they built and the resources to follow it.

That's the thread. Marcus chose the early shift. You decide what happens next.

DRAFT B (generic):
When Marcus enrolled in our literacy program, he had one goal: read well enough to help his daughter with homework. Within eight months, he was reading to her every night — and had earned a promotion he'd been passed over for twice before. "I made a decision," he says. "My family needed more from me, and I went and got it."

Marcus's story is one of hundreds we could tell. But only if we keep the doors open.

Year-end is our most critical fundraising moment. A gift of $50 today keeps one participant enrolled for a full month. Will you help write the next chapter?

DRAFT C (original preference):
When Marcus decided he wanted to read bedtime stories to his kids — actually read them, not just turn the pages — he signed up for our adult literacy program. He worked full-time, took the bus to class twice a week, and practiced on his lunch breaks. By spring, he was reading chapter books out loud to his daughter.

That's a choice. And it changes everything downstream.

This year, we're working to reach 200 more adults like Marcus. Each spot in our program costs $75. If you're able to give before December 31st, your gift directly opens that door for someone ready to walk through it.

RUBRIC CRITERIA (the user's personalized writing quality criteria):
{
  "rubric": [
    {
      "name": "Agency & Power in Language",
      "category": "Style",
      "description": "Community members, local partners, and program participants are the grammatical subjects of sentences, doing active verbs \u2014 they enrolled, chose, built, pursued. The organization appears in supporting clauses, not as the hero. The subject of the sentence encodes who holds power, and the user treats this as non-negotiable.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "community_as_subject",
          "label": "Community members and local partners are the grammatical subjects of key sentences, not the organization"
        },
        {
          "id": "active_verb_chains",
          "label": "Participants are described with active verbs (enrolled, chose, walked, built) rather than passive constructions or verbs of reception"
        },
        {
          "id": "org_supporting_role",
          "label": "The organization is positioned as enabler or supporter of community-driven action, not the primary actor"
        },
        {
          "id": "no_passive_beneficiaries",
          "label": "No sentences frame participants as things that programs happened to \u2014 literacy is something they pursued, not something delivered to them"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 1
    },
    {
      "name": "Donor Addressed as Decision-Maker",
      "category": "Audience",
      "description": "The donor is spoken to directly throughout the piece \u2014 not just at the opening thank-you or closing ask. Their role is framed around their decision to invest, not their generosity. The language acknowledges that the donor's choice enabled community capacity, rather than flattering them or positioning them as saviors.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "direct_address_throughout",
          "label": "The donor is addressed in second person ('you') at multiple points in the body of the piece, not only at the beginning or end"
        },
        {
          "id": "decision_not_generosity",
          "label": "Language frames the donor's contribution around their decision or investment, not their generosity or kindness"
        },
        {
          "id": "enabler_of_community",
          "label": "The donor is positioned as enabling what community members already knew how to do \u2014 not as providing charity"
        },
        {
          "id": "not_savior_framing",
          "label": "No language positions the donor as rescuing, saving, or giving to passive recipients"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 2
    },
    {
      "name": "Specific, Story-Tied Call to Action",
      "category": "Content",
      "description": "The ask connects directly to the narrative \u2014 a specific funding amount, a specific number of people, a specific timeframe \u2014 not a generic appeal. The reader should be able to draw a straight line from the opening story to what their next gift would do. The ask feels earned by the narrative, not appended to it.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "specific_amount",
          "label": "The ask includes a specific dollar amount or funding threshold"
        },
        {
          "id": "specific_impact",
          "label": "The ask names a specific number of people or families it would reach"
        },
        {
          "id": "specific_timeframe",
          "label": "The ask includes an honest, concrete timeframe for when the impact would be felt"
        },
        {
          "id": "tied_to_opening_story",
          "label": "The ask explicitly connects back to the person or moment from the opening narrative \u2014 the reader sees the thread"
        },
        {
          "id": "not_generic_appeal",
          "label": "The call to action could not be copy-pasted into a different organization's newsletter without modification"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 3
    },
    {
      "name": "Narrative-First Structure",
      "category": "Structure",
      "description": "The piece opens with one specific person's story \u2014 fully, without any statistics \u2014 before the lens widens to show scale. The reader meets a real person and sits with their choices before encountering any numbers. Numbers arrive in a separate section as evidence that this is not just one story.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "opens_with_person",
          "label": "The piece opens with a specific individual \u2014 named, situated, making a choice \u2014 before any programmatic framing"
        },
        {
          "id": "story_before_stats",
          "label": "No enrollment figures, program statistics, or scale numbers appear until after the opening narrative is complete"
        },
        {
          "id": "structural_separation",
          "label": "The individual story and the scale numbers occupy distinct sections, not the same paragraph or breath"
        },
        {
          "id": "numbers_earn_weight",
          "label": "Statistics land harder because the reader already cares about one person \u2014 the numbers feel like evidence, not a report"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 4
    },
    {
      "name": "Specificity Over Sentimentality",
      "category": "Content",
      "description": "Impact is conveyed through concrete, real details \u2014 names, moments, choices, places \u2014 rather than through adjectives, emotional language, or template-style warmth. The piece should feel like it could only have been written about this program, these people, this quarter. Warmth is welcome but must be earned by specificity.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "concrete_details",
          "label": "Key claims are grounded in specific, verifiable details rather than vague or general language"
        },
        {
          "id": "no_template_feeling",
          "label": "The piece could not describe a different program without substantial rewriting \u2014 it is particular to its subject"
        },
        {
          "id": "earned_emotion",
          "label": "Emotional moments arise from specific facts or narrative details, not from adjectives or declarative emotional statements"
        },
        {
          "id": "honest_framing",
          "label": "Challenges, limitations, or early-stage realities are acknowledged directly rather than glossed over"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 5
    }
  ],
  "version": 2,
  "source": "criteria_classification",
  "writing_type": "nonprofit donor communications",
  "user_goals_summary": "This user writes donor-facing communications that center community members as active agents, use narrative to earn emotional and financial investment, and treat donors as decision-makers rather than recipients of gratitude. They prioritize specificity over sentimentality and insist on structural sequencing where story precedes statistics and the call to action ties directly back to the narrative.",
  "coaching_notes": "This user is unusually precise about sentence-level power dynamics \u2014 who is the grammatical subject of a sentence is treated as a values question, not a stylistic one. Never default to organization-as-hero framing. They prefer incremental, additive revisions over wholesale rewrites and will explicitly lock sections they're satisfied with \u2014 respect those locks. Their strongest feedback comes in the form of structural sequencing instructions (what appears before what), so always clarify section order early."
}

RECENT CONVERSATION CONTEXT (shows the user's writing preferences and interactions):
munity 2], and [Community 3] — adults and children who identified the program, sought it out, and showed up. [X] of them are parents learning alongside their kids. [X] community members stepped forward to train as teachers and now lead classes in their own villages.

They built the foundation. Your decision to invest in this expansion gave them the resources to do what they already knew how to do.

---

**What It Took to Get Here**

The teachers who run these classrooms know their communities in ways no outside organization could. They identified who needed flexible hours. They adapted materials for Indigenous language speakers. They knocked on doors and answered questions from families who were uncertain.

[Quote from local teacher or community partner here — one sentence in their voice is worth a paragraph of organizational description.]

That work was already in them. What you made possible was the infrastructure around it — the classrooms, the materials, the time for teachers to train without losing income.

---

**What's Still Out of Reach**

The program is working. And the families who built it can't yet reach everyone who wants in.

In [Community X] alone, [X] families are on a waitlist right now. They've already decided they want this. They've already asked. The distance between them and a seat in a classroom isn't will or readiness — it's resources.

You've closed that distance before. Here's where it exists now.

---

**What You Can Do About That**

A gift of [specific amount] would bring [X] of those families off the waitlist and into the program by [honest, specific timeframe].

That's not a general funding appeal. That's [Name from your opening scene] — and the [X] families whose story looks like hers — getting the same opportunity that your support made possible for the first cohort.

[DONATE BUTTON / LINK / REPLY INSTRUCTIONS]

---

**Thank you for making the first expansion possible. Here's to the next one.**

[Signatory]
[Title, Organization Name]

[Contact info]
</draft>

Three additions, each framed around the donor's decision rather than their generosity:

- **"She's Not Alone"** — "your decision to invest" replaces the organizational voice
- **"What It Took"** — "what you made possible was the infrastructure" positions the donor as enabler of community knowledge, not provider of charity
- **"What's Still Out of Reach"** — "you've closed that distance before" creates a direct bridge into the ask

Nothing else moved.

